header.gameNote: FRONTIER COMMUNICATIONS AMERICAN ATHLETIC CONFERENCE WOMEN'S CHAMPIONSHIP - FINAL

article.description: Katie Lou Samuelson hit all 10 of her 3-point shots and scored 40 points to lead top-ranked UConn to a 100-44 rout of South Florida in the American Athletic Conference Tournament final.
article.headline: UConn wins AAC behind Katie Lou Samuelson's record-breaking night
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. -- Katie Lou Samuelson had a record-breaking night, scoring 40 points and hitting all 10 of her 3-point shots to lead top-ranked UConn to a 100-44 rout of South Florida in the American Athletic Conference Tournament final on Monday.

Samuelson set a Division I record for consecutive 3-pointers in a game and also set the tournament's single-game scoring mark.

Napheesa Collier added 15 points as the Huskies won their 107th straight game and extended their conference winning streak to 82 games.

UConn has not lost to an AAC opponent since the league was formed four seasons ago. And this one was never in doubt.

Samuelson scored eight points and hit her first two 3-pointers during an opening 12-0 run for the Huskies.

South Florida coach Jose Fernandez used three of his four timeouts in the first quarter in an attempt to slow UConn down, but Collier's buzzer-beating 3-pointer from the left corner made it 30-11 after one quarter.

Samuelson gave UConn (32-0) its first 40-point lead with her eighth shot from behind the arc in the second quarter. She had 29 points in the first half, and the Huskies, who did not trail at any point during the tournament, led 62-23 at the break.

Samuelson played just eight minutes in the second half.

Dorottya Nagy had a season-high 15 points and Kitija Laksa added 13 for South Florida (24-8).

The Huskies have beaten the Bulls in all 23 of their meetings, including the past three conference title games.

UConn has won 22 conference titles, dating to the program's days in the Big East. UConn has played in a conference tournament final in 27 of the past 29 years.

Exhaustion might have been a factor in this one for South Florida. Laksa, Laia Flores, Maria Jespersen and Ariadna Pujol played every minute of the team's first two tournament games. In Monday's blowout, Flores played 36 minutes, Laksa and Pujol each played 33 and Jespersen played 29.

The Huskies will host the first two rounds of the NCAA tournament in Storrs and are expected to be in the Bridgeport regional. That would mean the Huskies won't have to leave Connecticut before the Final Four in Dallas, should they advance that far.

South Florida is expected to be one of three AAC teams to receive an NCAA bid, joining UConn and Temple, which lost to the Bulls in the semifinals.
